The Renfrew County Murders Are Not An Anomaly
Everyone knew Basil Borutski was dangerous, and he had the criminal record to prove it. Then, in 2015, he killed three women in a single day, all of whom feared him. This week, Borutski was found guilty, but the case stands as a condemnation of an entire systemâ€™s failure to protect women.
By Sarah Boesveld
Updated November 28, 2017
Anastasia Kuzyk, Nathalie Warmerdam and Carol Culleton were murdered by Basil BorutskiÂ in 2015. Warmerdam photo courtesy of COPKA. Kuzyk and Culleton photos via Facebook.
On a clear September morningÂ in 2015,Â 57-year-oldÂ BasilÂ BorutskiÂ left his apartment in the Eastern Ontario hamlet of Palmer Rapids for the veryÂ last time.Â HeÂ slid behind the wheel of aÂ silverÂ Chrysler CirrusÂ borrowed from a friend, drove by thick forests, through the quaint village ofÂ CombermereÂ and pulled up beside a small brown cottage on LakeÂ Kamaniskeg. He had spent a lot of time there that summer, fixing up the property and trying to get closer to its owner, Carol Culleton, aÂ 66-year-oldÂ public servant from the Ottawa area heâ€™dÂ casually datedÂ a few years before. Culleton had grown tired ofÂ Borutskiâ€™sÂ recentÂ advances and repeatedly told him to stay away. Just two days earlier, she let him know she was seeing someone else.Â BorutskiÂ arrivedÂ atÂ her cottage in a jealous rage. AfterÂ CulletonÂ locked him out, he smashedÂ theÂ front door window, let himself in and wound aÂ coaxial television cable around Culletonâ€™s neck and jaw, cutting off her airway. He left her body slumped on the floor beside her bed, covered in a blanket.
